rComments: If you're taking this prof you comfortable getting graded at the end of the semester and having no feedback throughout the semester.
teacherRatingTags: ['Participation matters', 'Graded by few things', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: Great lectures and very knowledgeable in the field. No textbook but the readings were provided through brightspace. The readings and lectures are mandatory to succeed. Definitely isn't an easy course, you have to work for a good grade. I only received one mark during the semester, but if you ask for feedback it will be provided. Amazing prof!

Hes very knowledgeable in his field and expects participation from his students based on the lectures. His time management skills are very poor though, very limited availability this semester and many emails were unanswered or answered very late. I had to email him to get the breakdown of my final grade, I received no feedback during the semester.

He was one of the best professors I've had throughout university. I was in his Advanced Topics in Critical Security and War the semester we shifted to online learning. Although I only had one course with him, I can't speak highly enough of him.

This is the Model UN class... You guys there's no structure whatsoever in this class and when you're learning about diplomacy, you should have classes that teach you what paper do to and how to do it... Not exactly sure what he has in mind when he's thinking of a learn as you go while evaluating you on exactly what he doesn't show in class...
Professor Larrinaga is excellent, his seminar was interesting and he encourages participation, in general I liked this course. However the reading is excessive.
teacherRatingTags: ['Lots of homework', 'Get ready to read', 'Participation matters']

rComments: I had never struggled as much in my university path as with him. He seems to think that his class is the only one we have so there are around 100 pages to read per week and you need to read in order to participate in the seminars in order to get a good grade. Readings are boring and so are his lectures. great human being but AVOID AT ALL COSTS.
teacherRatingTags: ['Lots of homework', 'Get ready to read', 'Lecture heavy']

rComments: He picks really great readings and delivers great lectures. Expect seminar-style lectures with slides and lots of engaging class discussion. You get graded on participation, reading summaries, a film review, an essay, and final take-home exam.

Great guy. Sharp thinker. Knows the content. Linked in with the top scholars in the topic. Appreciates all comments and tries to work with whatever comes his way. My time in his class was extremely formative and valuable. Great prof, 10/10.

De Larrinaga is a very engaging lecturer. I loved the discussions in this course. My only critique is that you don't receive marks back until the end of the semester. Regardless, I would definitely recommend his course. You will not be disappointed.
UNREAL. Although he is slow to return marks, he provides good feedback and prepares you well for NMUN.
teacherRatingTags: ['Participation matters', 'Gives good feedback', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: I took the Model UN class with Miguel and I sincerely believe our delegation had such an amazing experience because of the way he taught and treated us. He wasn't the clearest lecturer and was definitely monotone at times but in the end, he did everything he could to help us grow and do a good job in New York. Very knowledgeable also!
Really chill prof who is clear and fair. Very interesting and acknowledgeable. Not too many readings or assignments, but participation is important.

Demonstrated a thorough understanding of the material presented, could be much better at facilitating and stimulating discussions (esp for a seminar), did not give back any grades until the end of the semester, a mediocre but very kind professor.

Miguel is a good prof, but his lectures last forever. This is not his fault; its because IR theory is extremely boring. A lot of what he lectures on is confusing, but if you sit down and study, everything will make sense. My biggest problem is that he has mandatory discussion groups (that require more than just showing up and participating).
teacherRatingTags: ['Gives good feedback', 'Get ready to read', 'Participation matters']

rComments: De Larrinaga is an extremely nice prof, the only downside to taking his course is that the lectures seem like forever because the way he teaches the material is so dry. He does well for what he's working with, however. Assignment feedback was good, and gave a chance to resubmit for a better mark. Posts everything to blackboard, mostly reads slides.

Professor De Larrinaga is very intelligent, however he completely loses you in his lecture. His slides make no sense and trying to study off of them is nearly impossible. He's not a hard marker but the class is very painful to sit through.

Brutal lecturer, always confusing and skipping around on his powerpoints. Makes up words on the spot and uses large words out of context in an effort to pretend to be smart.  Nice man in office hours, but useless as a professor.

Great Prof! He has a lot of knowledge on the topic. BUT his lecture slides don't have a lot of content and some of the terms in class are not clearly defined. He gave out the final exam questions which was good and it helped to focus studying!
Lots of readings. Gave exam questions prior to exam.  Go see his office hours, he genuinely wants you to succeed, which can't be said for all profs! One of the best in the department

I took two classes with this professor (POL4124 and POL2103) and enjoyed them both. Readings are intense, but are mostly online so that saves money. 4th year is all about discussion so be prepared for class. Requires long essays, so make sure you pick a topic that interests you otherwise it's a long semester.

Deeper understanding of the texts that isn't explicitly stated during the course is needed. Do the readings and try to "understand" them not just know them. Lots of concept comparison stuff for essays. Obviously, for seminars, go to class.

Excellent prof - extremely approachable and genuinely wants his students to understand the material and succeed. Very knowledgeable. Only criticism is that he never hands back papers and you hand in 75% of your coursework in the last week of classes.

The man definitely has interesting things to say, but he'll ramble on about his slides , which are pretty much what evaluations are based on. Make sure to keep up with the readings though, all he does is summarize them when the evaluations are actually based on a deeper understanding of them. Pro-tip, I guess.
Great class, amazing professor! The Prof is very helpful and clearly outlines his expectations. Highly recommend this class even to those who aren't forced to take IR.
great guy! very fair. A lot of reading

One of the best profs I've had.  Took 3 class with him throughout my studies.  Helpful, resourceful, very knowledgable.  His marking is hard but you definatly want to put the effort in and you learn a lot from his teaching.

Prof de Larrinaga is probably one of the nicest...no, is definitely the nicest prof I've ever had. He genuinely wants to help, is interested in the subject matter and is obviously an expert in it. You have to put forth a huge effort to do well, but that's what we're here for, right? Only negative: slow at handing things back.

A very intelligent man who seems genuinely interested in the subject matter and wants to teach. Unfortunately, his communication skills are lacking. He seems incapable of speaking without a page in front of him, and his lecture slides (not provided online) are absolutely filled with text - too much to absorb in one sitting.

He is an extremely intelligent man. He is very nice, very helpful, and loves class discussions and the exchange of ideas. His course is not a bird course, but you learn a LOT of things [even if you're a poli-sci nerd]. If you like politics, you'll love this class.
Cutting edge approach to IR. Understands all theoretical backgrounds very well, and is the best prof I've had in IR so far.
He's a tough marker, and his exams are deceptively challenging but overall he's a great guy.

VERY intelligent guy, speaks 4 or 5 languages, English being his second. Has crazy vocabulary, so this has also been an English class for me. No notes on the web, slides in class but hardly have any time to copy them down. You really have to pay attention in this class. The material is very abstract. No textbook, just a collection of readings.
WTF?  I have no idea what my grade is because he doesn't hand things back... TOTAL BS.

Took a class that was supposed to be on security, globalization and development and turned it into a class on the meaning of security and its etymologies. One of the most abstract and boring classes I have ever taken.

Prof. De Larrinaga is an extremely intelligent man.  The course itself is structured in a logical manner, but the prof sometimes cannot convey the material in a clear manner.  Lots of reading each week, much of which is pretty complex.  The prof "uhmms" and "ahhhs" a lot, but a very smart man nonetheless.

he is a very smart prof, however he lacks the ability to clearly articulate the info to students. he was unable to hold my attention, and i often got lost on his tangants. i had to buy an extra textbook to understand what was going on in the class...
SOOO off topic sometimes. He is TOO SMART! Loved him, VERY challanging, but rewarding if u get through, YOU WILL LEARN SOO MUCH

very unorganized. no logic to lectures. he cannot convey what he wants to the students. Personally, I can't sit through one of his lecutres. he looses my attention after about 20mins. The information in the course is not taught, and his reader is far to complex and expensive
Wastes alot of time.
great prof., very smart, you just have to wanna study...

NOT ORGANIZED - material isn't easy and he does not convey it well - and the TA for his class was a complete **** - classes are easy but you have to learn the material on your own - and that's when it becomes a huge huge challenge.
He's all over the place, his lectures are not organized at all. Subject matter is interesting, the TA'S very picky markers. Prof is a nice guy, but not organized at all!
